Day 22 - Introduction to Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)

Today I continued my Python learning journey and started learning the basics of Object-Oriented Programming (OOP).

At first, I created a class called Mobil with two attributes: merk and tahun. Through this exercise, I learned how a class acts as a blueprint and how objects can be created from that blueprint.

I also learned about:

- Classes
- Objects
- Attributes
- Methods
- The use of self
- Constructors (init)

After creating the basic class, I added an info() method to display the car's brand and year.

Next, I created an umur_mobil() method that calculates the age of a car using the current year. While doing this, I made a small mistake by using curly braces in a mathematical operation, but I learned the difference between f-strings and normal calculations.

Finally, I completed the ganti_merk() method. This challenge helped me understand how object attributes can be modified after an object is created. I also learned the difference between working with dictionaries and working with objects, which was confusing at first but became much clearer after practice.

Today's achievement:

- Successfully built a Mobil class
- Added multiple methods
- Calculated values using object attributes
- Updated object attributes
- Improved my understanding of OOP fundamentals

Challenges:

- Understanding self
- Distinguishing between dictionaries and objects
- Reading and fixing NameError messages

Reflection:
Today reminded me that making mistakes is a normal part of programming. Most of my errors came from misunderstanding concepts, not from a lack of effort. By debugging and fixing them one by one, I gained a better understanding of how Python classes and objects work.

